            <pb facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Universal Diffusion of Life.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;Since the time<lb break="yes"/>when, in an earlier work, I attempted to
                    describe the<lb break="yes"/>universal diffusion of organic life on the surface
                    of the<lb break="yes"/>globe, and its distribution in height and in depth,
                        our<lb break="yes"/>knowledge has been wonderfully augmented by Ehren-<lb
                        break="no"/>berg&#x2019;s brilliant discoveries, which rest not on
                        ingenious<lb break="yes"/>combinations and inferences, but on direct and
                        exact<lb break="yes"/>observations. By these discoveries the sphere of
                        ani-<lb break="no"/>mated existence&#x2014;we may say the horizon of
                        life&#x2014;has<lb break="yes"/>expanded before our view. Not only is there
                    no inter-<lb break="no"/>ruption of minute microscopic forms of animal life in
                        the<lb break="yes"/>vicinity of either pole, where larger animals cannot<lb
                        break="yes"/>maintain themselves<choice><sic>.</sic><corr type="editorial"
                            >,</corr></choice> but we find among the microscopic<lb break="yes"
                    />animals of the South Polar Seas, collected in the An-<lb break="no"/>tarctic
                    expedition of Captain James Ross, a remarkable<lb break="yes"/>abundance of new
                    forms, which are often of great<lb break="yes"/>elegance. Even in the residuum
                    obtained from melted<lb break="yes"/>ice, which floats in rounded fragments in
                        latitude<lb break="yes"/>78 deg. 10 min. S, there have been found above
                        fifty<lb break="yes"/>species of siliceous-shelled polygastrica, and even<lb
                        break="yes"/>coscinodisc&#x00E6; with green ovaries, which were, there-<lb
                        break="no"/>fore, certainly living, and <choice><sic>not able</sic><corr
                            type="editorial">able</corr></choice> to resist the ex-<lb break="no"
                    />treme severity of the cold. It is not only in particular<lb break="yes"
                    />localities, in inland waters, or in the vicinity of<lb break="yes"/>coasts,
                    that the ocean is thus thickly peopled with<lb break="yes"/>living atoms
                    invisible to the naked eye. Samples of<lb break="yes"/>water taken up by Schayer
                    in 57 deg. S latitude,<lb break="yes"/>on his return from Van Dieman&#x2019;s
                    Land, as well as<lb break="yes"/>those taken between the tropies in the middle
                    of the<lb break="yes"/>Atlantic, show that the ocean water, in its ordinary<lb
                        break="yes"/>condition, without any appearance of discolouration,<lb
                        break="yes"/>contains innumerable microscopic organisms, quite dis-<lb
                        break="no"/>tinct from the siliceous filaments of the genus ch&#x00E6;-<lb
                        break="no"/>toceros, floating in a fragmentary state like the<lb break="yes"
                    />osciliatoria of our fresh waters. Some polygastrica<lb break="yes"/>which have
                    been found mixed with sand and excre-<lb break="no"/>ments of penguins in the
                    Cockburn Islands appear to<lb break="yes"/>be generally distributed over the
                    globe; other species<lb break="yes"/>belong to both the Arctic and Antarctic
                    Polar regions.<lb break="yes"/>Thus we see that animal life reigns in the
                        perpetual<lb break="yes"/>night of the depths of the ocean; while on
                        continents,<lb break="yes"/>vegetable life, stimulated by the periodical
                    action of<lb break="yes"/>the solar rays, chiefly predominates. Not only are<lb
                        break="yes"/>earth, air, and water, filled with life, and that at the<lb
                        break="yes"/>most different temperatures, but also the interior of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>various parts of animal bodies; there are animalcula in<lb
                        break="yes"/>the blood of frogs and of salmon; according to 
                    <choice><sic>Nord-<lb break="no"/>man</sic><corr type="editorial">Nord-<lb break="no"/>mann</corr></choice>, the fluids of the eyes of fishes are often filled with<lb
                        break="yes"/>a worm which lives by suction (diplostomum); and the<lb
                        break="yes"/>same naturalist has even discovered in the gills of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>bleak an extraordinary double animal (diploson para-<lb
                        break="no"/>doxon) having two heads and two caudal extremities<lb
                        break="yes"/>disposed in rectangular directions.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i"
                        >Humboldt&#x2019;s Cosmos.</hi>
                </p>
